# AuthService — Full Explanation

## What is AuthService?

AuthService is a **dedicated class or layer** whose only job is to handle **authentication and authorization logic** separately from your UserService.

---

## The Problem Without AuthService

Right now in your project, your UserService is doing too many jobs at once:

```
UserService is currently doing:
- Saving user to DB          ← that is USER management
- Checking duplicate email   ← that is USER management
- Encoding password          ← that is USER management
- Matching password on login ← that is AUTHENTICATION
- Generating JWT token       ← that is AUTHENTICATION
- Returning token            ← that is AUTHENTICATION
```

This breaks the **Single Responsibility Principle** which says one class should do only one job.

---

## What AuthService Does

```
UserService  → ONLY manages user data
               register, update, delete, get user

AuthService  → ONLY handles authentication
               login, validate credentials,
               generate token, refresh token
```

---

## Visual Difference

### Without AuthService (What you have now)
```
UserController
      ↓
UserService
  ├── register()     ← user management ✅
  ├── login()        ← authentication ⚠️ mixed in
  └── generateToken  ← jwt logic ⚠️ mixed in
```

### With AuthService (Clean separation)
```
UserController ──► UserService
                     └── register()    ← only user management

AuthController ──► AuthService
                     ├── login()       ← only authentication
                     └── generateToken ← only jwt logic
```

---

## What AuthService Contains

```
AuthService does these jobs:

1. login(LoginDTO)
   → Find user by email
   → Match password
   → If correct → call JwtUtil to generate token
   → Return token

2. validateToken(String token)
   → Call JwtUtil to validate
   → Return true or false

3. getLoggedInUser(String token)
   → Extract email from token
   → Fetch user from DB
   → Return user details
```

---

## What AuthController Contains

```
AuthController exposes these endpoints:

POST /api/auth/login
   → Takes email + password
   → Returns JWT token

GET  /api/auth/validate
   → Takes token
   → Returns valid or invalid

GET  /api/auth/me
   → Takes token
   → Returns logged in user details
```

---

## How It Fits Into Your Project

```
Your Pharmacy Project after adding AuthService:

User-Service
  ├── UserController   → /api/users/register
  ├── UserService      → register only
  │
  ├── AuthController   → /api/auth/login
  │                       /api/auth/validate
  │                       /api/auth/me
  └── AuthService      → login, validate, getLoggedInUser
```

---

## How Other Microservices Use AuthService

```
Currently:
Order-Service validates JWT locally using its own JwtUtil

Future upgrade possibility:
Order-Service calls User-Service AuthService
to validate token centrally

But for your current project:
Each service validates JWT locally — this is fine
AuthService just cleans up the User-Service internally
```

---

## SecurityConfig Connection

```
Without AuthService:
SecurityConfig → only blocks/allows endpoints

With AuthService:
SecurityConfig → uses AuthService to load user details
                 when Spring Security needs to verify
                 who is making the request

AuthService implements UserDetailsService
→ Spring Security calls loadUserByUsername()
→ AuthService fetches user from DB by email
→ Spring Security compares passwords internally
```

---

## UserDetailsService — The Key Interface

This is the most important part of AuthService in Spring Security:

```
Spring Security has a built-in interface called UserDetailsService
It has one method: loadUserByUsername(String email)

When you implement this in AuthService:
→ Spring Security knows how to fetch YOUR users from YOUR DB
→ It handles the password matching automatically
→ It sets up the security context properly

Without this:
→ You manually match passwords in service
→ Spring Security does not know about your users
```

---

## Summary Table

| | UserService | AuthService |
|---|---|---|
| Register user | ✅ | ❌ |
| Save to DB | ✅ | ❌ |
| Login | ❌ | ✅ |
| Generate JWT | ❌ | ✅ |
| Validate token | ❌ | ✅ |
| Load user for Spring Security | ❌ | ✅ |
| Implements UserDetailsService | ❌ | ✅ |

---

## Should You Add It To Your Project?

```
YES — because:
✅ Cleaner code structure
✅ Single responsibility followed
✅ Spring Security integrates properly
✅ Easy to add refresh token later
✅ Easy to add OAuth or Google login later
✅ Industry standard pattern
```

